{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_013HmAY21J55nxHXbAsEetDW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me analyze the patterns:\n\n**Pattern 1 (12 failures): Ingredient bullet lines** — The actual titles (like \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\", \"SERNIK\", \"GARLIC BRUSCHETTA\") are ALL_CAPS and appear early, but somehow lose to ingredient lines like \"- 2 jajka\" or \"- Salt to taste\".\n\nLooking at the structure more carefully:\n- Barszcz Czerwony: `SKŁADNIKI` (line 0) → `BARSZCZ CZERWONY` (line 2) → `- 2 jajka` (line 4)\n\n\n- Sernik: `SERNIK` (line 0) → `skladniki` (line 2) → ingredients\n- Garlic Bruschetta: garbled page header → `GARLIC BRUSCHETTA` (line 2) → `INGREDIENTS:` → ingredients\n\nThe issue is clear now — the multi-title guard is triggering when it shouldn't, selecting ingredient lines instead of the actual recipe titles because they appear later in the document structure. I'm tracing through the logic for BARSZCZ CZERWONY — the next lines like \"- 2 jajka\" don't match the ingredient detection patterns, so it's not classified as a subheader. This means both SKŁADNIKI and BARSZCZ CZERWONY end up in the selected array, and after deduplication and sorting by position, they both survive in the output. checks the next two lines after BARSZCZ CZERWONY to determine if it's a subheader. At position 2, that would be the empty line and \"- 2 jajka\", neither of which match ingredient patterns, so isSubHeader returns false. Let me trace through the logic more carefully to see where the classification is going wrong. Neither triggers looksLikeIngredient or startsWithNumber. So isSubHeader = false.\n\nBut then allCapsSelected has SKŁADNIKI and BARSZCZ CZERWONY. Since isSubHeader = false, `selected = allCapsSelected`. Both survive.\n\nResult would be \"SKŁADNIKI + BARSZCZ CZERWONY\".\n\nBut the feedback says the result is \"- 2 jajka\". So something else must be happening. Let me think...\n\nMaybe SKŁADNIKI doesn't pass threshold? Or maybe the scoring is different. Or maybe there's something else going on.\n\nActually, I realize I don't have the full trace. The feedback says the output is \"- 2 jajka\" for Barszcz Czerwony. Let me think about what scoring mechanism would lead to this.\n\nSKŁADNIKI means \"ingredients\" — it would embed close to the header reference, giving it a negative rawScore, so it likely fails the threshold. BARSZCZ CZERWONY is a dish name that should embed reasonably close to the title reference, but the Polish text might not create strong similarity to the English reference in MiniLM, resulting in a low rawScore. If both fail their thresholdScore checks, they'd be filtered out, leaving only the ingredient line \"- 2 jajka\".\n\nThe core issues are that bullet-prefixed lines aren't being filtered, Polish ingredient keywords aren't recognized, and section headers like SKŁADNIKI aren't being caught by the current logic.\n\nI need to implement four specific fixes: add a bullet-line filter to passesHardFilters, expand ingredient detection to include Polish units and \"do smaku\" patterns, filter out known section labels, and fix isSubHeader to not assume the first all-caps word is always the title. These changes should resolve all the failures.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":655,"cache_read_input_tokens":48796,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":655},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"866f68b5-3ea0-400d-9a2a-138f41106e3f","uuid":"53f40bdd-1c45-4fa5-8b29-5bf18c36ea22"}
